if i apply to fafsa as an independent how much money should i be doing during the year they will check my taxes and depend on that they will decide how much money will i receive i'm already i just want keep studying hi it dosen't matter how much money you make if you are applying for a loan but if it is for a pell grant then no more than a year the more you earn the more your grant goes down you can be an independent student to apply or a dependent under the federal pell grant program provides need based grants to low income undergraduate and certain postbaccalaureate students to promote access to postsecondary education students may use their grants at any one of approximately participating postsecondary institutions grant amounts are dependent on the student s expected family contribution efc see below the cost of attendance as determined by the institution the student s enrollment status full time or part time and whether the student attends for a full academic year or less students may not receive federal pell grant funds from more than one school at a time financial need is determined by the department of education using a standard formula established by congress to evaluate the financial information reported on the free application for federal student aid fafsa and to determine the family efc the fundamental elements in this standard formula are the student s income and assets if the student is independent the parents income and assets if the student is dependent the family s household size and the number of family members excluding parents attending postsecondary institutions the efc is the sum of a percentage of net income remaining income after subtracting allowances for basic living expenses and taxes and a percentage of net assets assets remaining after subtracting an asset protection allowance different assessment rates and allowances are used for dependent students independent students without dependents and independent students with dependents after filing a fafsa the student receives a student aid report sar or the institution receives an institutional student information record isir which notifies the student if he or she is eligible for a federal pell grant and provides the student s efc Student loan Education in the People's Republic of China College admissions Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Taxation in the United States Education in Japan Social Security (United States) Graduate school 401(k) Microeconomics Education in Hong Kong FairTax Food Stamp Program Divorce United Kingdom corporation tax Money supply Affirmative action Inflation University of Pretoria Education in England Unemployment benefit Insurance Social Security debate (United States) Credit card Economy of India Personal finance Separation of church and state Capitalism Professor Federal Reserve Bretton Woods system Education in Portugal Grade (education) Annuity Physician Tertiary education fees in Australia Wal-Mart Microcredit Publicly funded medicine GED Education Education in Germany Flat tax Derivative (finance) Columbia University Child support Government agencies in Sweden School choice Law school International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement Corporate finance Inheritance tax Public domain Mortgage Government debt U.S. generally accepted accounting principles Income statement College Centrelink Barbara Boxer Education in Australia Monetary policy Corporation University of Michigan Education in New Zealand Establishment Clause of the First Amendment Productive and unproductive labour College and university rankings Conscription Minimum wage Kyoto Protocol University of Central Florida University of Toronto Marshall Plan British nationality law Software patent debate United States Postal Service Financial services Credit union George W. Bush 